<div id="review_2356890808" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2356890808" />
    <a title="A.B. Funkhauser" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41622637-a-b-funkhauser"><img alt="A.B. Funkhauser" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1427488362p2/41622637.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2356890808?book_show_action=true">Apr 10, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="A.B. Funkhauser" class="user" itemprop="url" name="A.B. Funkhauser" href="/user/show/41622637-a-b-funkhauser">A.B. Funkhauser</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2356890808" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6885003559188998756">TERROR IN JERSEY<br/><br/>There’s something very cool about author John DeBoer’s latest outing. Moving beyond mystery he explores ideological warfare—in this case, home grown terrorism—with an eye to the family unit. Ex-Navy SEAL Adam Taylor works for a security contractor with anchors in some of the world’s most dangerous places. Averting kidnaps, torture and death for radical agendas are part of his job description. His tasks are far from rote, but when an ISIS executioner plots a Boston-style bombing i</span>
  <span id="freeText6885003559188998756" style="display:none">TERROR IN JERSEY<br /><br />There’s something very cool about author John DeBoer’s latest outing. Moving beyond mystery he explores ideological warfare—in this case, home grown terrorism—with an eye to the family unit. Ex-Navy SEAL Adam Taylor works for a security contractor with anchors in some of the world’s most dangerous places. Averting kidnaps, torture and death for radical agendas are part of his job description. His tasks are far from rote, but when an ISIS executioner plots a Boston-style bombing in Taylor’s own backyard, his investment increases a thousandfold. Friends, colleagues, neighbors and even his shotgun-toting mom will join forces to protect their home. And this is what makes the story unique. Taylor’s family, home, town, city and country form a seamless unit that serves as a grand metaphor to Taylor’s self and psyche: Who are you and what are you willing to do to safeguard your soul is the overarching question and we read on to find out just that. Taylor is backed by a huge cast that includes FBI, CIA, NSA, the local constabulary and regular folks he grew up with. I enjoyed When the Reaper Comes not just for its colorful villains and matchless heroes, but for the detail DeBoer lends to his narrative. From the nuts and bolts planning behind a counter terrorist op to the military ordnance required to deliver results fascinated from beginning to end. 5 Stars for a good time and a super ending.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6885003559188998756" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


